<TITLE> De Beers 2007 rough diamond sales dip to $5.9 bln </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - De Beers, the world's top diamond producer, posted a 3.7 percent fall in natural rough diamond sales in 2007 to $5.92 billion due to tighter supplies. Jewellery demand in 2007 was healthy, but the outlook for this year was uncertain, hit by global economic conditions, the company said in a statement on Friday. "The economic conditions in the U.S. could continue to impact consumer diamond jewellery sales through the first half particularly at the lower end," it said. "Nevertheless, we expect strong demand from China, India and the Middle East to sustain pricing for larger and better quality diamonds." De Beers' contribution to underlying earnings of mining group Anglo American, which holds a 45-percent stake in the group, rose to $239 million from $227 million reported for 2006. Diamond production was flat at 51 million carats while earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortisation dipped by 1 percent to $1.2 billion, the group said. The company warned that electricity supply problems in South Africa could hit output there. The government has said it would seek to maintain power at 90 percent of normal levels, but if it dipped below this, problems could be serious, De Beers said. "Below this (90 percent) level the impact on production will be significant and could be in excess of 10 percent," De Beers said. South Africa has been hit by a power crisis that has blacked out homes, brought traffic to a standstill and halted mines for five days in the world's top platinum produc
